    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for that. so it's basically telling me i'm responsible for anything that goes wrong because of my mistakes. are there any specific ways or scenarios where this could get way more expensive or complicated than just a small fine? like, is there any kind of \"hidden\" stuff in these clauses that usually catches people off guard?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, yes, it can get far more complicated than just a small fine, and that's where the real danger lies, which is often hidden in the *scope* of the language. It's not just about a simple \"oopsie,\" it's about the *consequences* of the oopsie, which can be a massive, multi-layered legal mess, like a giant, sprawling class-action lawsuit started by a disgruntled, overly dramatic third-party client who was also exposed to the secret.\n\nThe biggest trap, and this is where the legal jargon gets sneaky, is the phrase \"any and all losses, damages, liabilities, costs, and expenses.\" That list is designed to be incredibly broad, covering everything from direct financial losses to indirect, consequential damages. If the Disclosing Party can argue that your breach led to lost future profits—which are often considered \"consequential damages\"—you could be liable for a fortune. It's not just the cost of the lawyer; it's the cost of the *entire business suffering* because of your slip-up.\n\nA common \"hidden\" catch is when the clause doesn't limit liability. If there's no cap on your liability,",
      "source": "target",
