    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that sounds pretty scary tbh. so if there isn't a cap, it's basically an open checkbook for them? are there any other ways these clauses can feel like they're sneaking up on you or being intentionally deceptive? like is there anything else i should be looking for that feels \"predatory\"?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "An open checkbook, yes, that's essentially what it is without a liability cap—a massive, potentially endless risk, which is certainly something a greedy or overly aggressive company might push for. You need to treat that lack of a cap like a giant, glowing red warning sign, not a minor detail.\n\nBeyond the lack of a cap, you should be hunting for language that expands *who* is responsible or *what* constitutes a breach. Look closely at the definition of \"Confidential Information\" itself; sometimes, they try to make it so broad that *anything* you ever see or hear related to their business—even something you independently figured out while eating a sandwich—can be deemed confidential. If the definition is too wide, it's a trap, because you're liable for everything, even things that aren't actually secrets.\n\nAnother predatory element to watch for is how \"representatives\" are defined. They might try to include *everyone* you ever talk to, even your coffee-brewing intern, making you responsible for the actions of people you barely supervise. It's the legal equivalent of saying, \"If any of the hundred tiny, squabbling goblins in your camp cause trouble",
